{#
  Example 09 — Custom rendering via the `{% call %}` block.

  Nunjucks has no render props, so `{% call %}` is its equivalent of
  "children". The shipped themeChooser macro checks `caller` and, when
  present, renders the block body INSIDE the button in place of the
  default `<span class="theme-chooser-icon">◑</span>`.

  That is the whole extension point. The root <div>, the hidden
  input, the button's ARIA attributes, and the <ul role="listbox">
  with one <li role="option"> per theme are all still emitted by the
  macro, so the client.js keyboard contract works unchanged.

  Two variants below:

    A. Inline `{% call %}` — override the glyph at one call site.
    B. A wrapper macro (themeChooserCustom.njk) that bakes the same
       glyph in for a whole project.

  The glyph must be aria-hidden="true": the button is icon-only, so
  its accessible name has to come from aria-label alone.

  Nothing here renders <option> elements. That was the old
  native-<select> behaviour and no longer applies — see
  ../docs/custom-rendering.md.
#}
{% from "../theme-chooser.njk" import themeChooser %}
{% from "./themeChooserCustom.njk" import themeChooserCustom %}

{# A. Inline glyph override. #}
{% call themeChooser({
    label: "Theme",
    id: "inline-theme",
    themesUrl: "/assets/themes/",
    themes: ["light", "dark", "abyss", "cupcake", "dracula"],
    storageKey: "lily:theme"
}) %}
    <span class="my-glyph" aria-hidden="true">&#9681;</span>
{% endcall %}

{# B. Same override, factored into a project-local wrapper macro.
     Note the distinct `id`: both controls default to name="theme",
     so without it their listbox and option ids would collide. #}
{{ themeChooserCustom({
    label: "Theme",
    id: "wrapped-theme",
    themesUrl: "/assets/themes/",
    themes: ["light", "dark", "abyss", "cupcake", "dracula"],
    storageKey: "lily:theme"
}) }}

<script type="module">
    import { initThemeChooser } from "../theme-chooser.client.js";
    document
        .querySelectorAll("[data-lily-theme-chooser-root]")
        .forEach((root) => initThemeChooser(root));
</script>
